'''Willis Group Holdings plc''' is a [[Multinational corporation|multinational]] risk advisor, [[insurance broker]]age and [[reinsurance]] brokerage company with its headquarters in the [[Willis Building (London)|Willis Building]] in London. It is the world's third-largest insurance broker when measured by revenues.<ref>[http://www2.iii.org/financial-services-fact-book/world-rankings.html ''World<U+2019>s Largest Insurance Brokers by Revenues, 2009''], Financial Services Fact Book 2011, p. 192.  Insurance Information Institute, ISBN 9780932387486.</ref> Willis has around 400 offices in 120 countries and approximately 17,000 employees.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/External.File?item=UGFyZW50SUQ9NTc1MjR8Q2hpbGRJRD0tMXxUeXBlPTM=&t=1 |title=Willis Group Holdings Fact Book| accessdate=21 August 2010|publisher=Willis Group Holdings}}</ref>

Willis acts as an intermediary between its clients and insurance carriers, advising its clients on [[risk management]] requirements, helping them determine the best way to manage [[risk]], and negotiating and placing insurance risk with insurance carriers.<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=ERpcoRmLTdwC&pg=PT437&dq=%22Willis+Group+Holdings%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=5#v=onepage&q=%22Willis%20Group%20Holdings%22&f=false ''Plunkett's Insurance Industry Almanac 2006: The Only Complete Reference To The Insurance And Risk Management Industry''], Jack W. Plunkett, Plunkett Research, Ltd., 2005, ISBN 1-59392-038-5. Retrieved 17 December 2009</ref>  It has major clients in the aerospace, marine, construction, and energy industries.<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=AzSWl06nrrUC&pg=PT438&dq=%22Willis+Group+Holdings%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=8#v=onepage&q=%22Willis%20Group%20Holdings%22&f=false ''Plunkett's Insurance Industry Almanac 2007 (E-Book): Insurance Industry Market Research, Statistics, Trends and Leading Companies''],  Jack W. Plunkett, Plunkett Research, Ltd., 2006, ISBN 1-59392-405-4. Retrieved 17 December 2009</ref>

Willis is listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]].

The Willis Group is not related to Willis Lease Finance Corporation of [[Novato, California]] ([[Nasdaq]]: WLFC)

== History ==
[[File:Willis Building (London).jpg|thumb|left|160px|The [[Willis Building (London)|Willis Building]] in London]]
The company was founded by Henry Willis in London in 1828, and initially operated as ''Henry Willis & Co.''<ref name=history>[http://www.willis.com/About_Willis/History/ Willis: History]</ref> In 1898 it merged with ''Faber Brothers'' (founded in 1886) to form ''Willis Faber'',<ref name=history/> and then in 1928 it merged with ''Dumas & Wylie'' (founded in 1843) to create ''Willis, Faber & Dumas''.<ref name=history/> It was first listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]] in 1976 as ''Willis Faber''.<ref name=history/>

It expanded into the United States in 1990 when it merged with ''Corroon & Black'' (founded as ''R. A. Corroon & Co.'' in 1905) to form the ''Willis Corroon Group''.<ref name=history/> In 1998 in a leveraged [[buyout]] the Company was acquired by ''Trinity Acquisition'' on behalf of [[Kohlberg Kravis Roberts]],<ref name=history/> and in 1999 the name ''Willis Group'' was adopted.<ref name=history/> It was first listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] in 2001.<ref name=history/>

In October 2008, Willis acquired ''[[Hilb, Rogal & Hobbs Co.]]'' (HRH), one of the largest insurance and risk management intermediaries in North America and this has boosted their North American presence, as well as acquired Glencairn LImited which has augmented its Lloyd's of London Market strength.<ref>[http://www.businessweek.com/bwdaily/dnflash/content/jun2008/db2008068_039462.htm Insurance broker Willis to buy HRH], ''[[Business Week]]'', June 2008</ref>

Willis announced plans in 2009 to relocate its registered office from [[Bermuda]] to Ireland.<ref>[http://www.willis.com/Media_Room/Press_Releases_(Browse_All)/2009/20090921_Willis_Redomestication_Press_Release_-_FINAL/ Willis Proposes Change in Place of Incorporation to Ireland], Press Release</ref>  Its shareholders approved the move in December 2009, and the company announced on 31 December 2009, that its reorganisation has been completed and the new parent company of the Willis Group <U+2013> known as Willis Group Holdings Public Limited Company <U+2013> is incorporated in Ireland.<ref>[http://www.willis.com/Investor_Relations/Financial_Press_Releases_%28Browse_All%29/2009/20091231_Willis_Completes_Change_in_Place_of_Incorporation_to_Ireland_31-12-2009/ "Willis Investor Relations"], 31 December 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.cnbc.com/id/34380843 "Willis Group holders agree to move co. to Ireland"], [[Associated Press]], 11 December 2009. Retrieved 17 December 2009</ref>

==Buildings==
[[File:KM 6167 sears tower august 2007 D.jpg|thumb|right|130px|The [[Willis Tower]] in Chicago]]
Willis moved into the [[Willis Building (London)|Willis Building]], its new London headquarters, in May 2008.<ref>[http://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/index.php?fuseaction=wanappln.projectview&upload_id=2283 Crunch? And the Willis building is sold],'' World Architecture News'', 13 May 2008</ref>

The [[Willis Building (Ipswich)|Willis Building]] in [[Ipswich]], England, is one of the earliest buildings designed by [[Norman Foster, Baron Foster of Thames Bank|Norman Foster]] after establishing [[Foster and Partners|Foster Associates]]. Constructed between 1970 and 1975 it is now seen as a landmark in the development of the 'high tech' architectural style.  It is one of the youngest buildings to be given [[Grade I listed building]] status in Britain.<ref>{{cite web | title=Pioneering management guidelines for modern listed buildings | url=http://ihbc.org.uk/context_archive/47/williscarroon.htm |publisher=Context | date = September 1995}}</ref> 

The 108-story [[Willis Tower|Sears Tower]] in Chicago was renamed the Willis Tower in July 2009.  Willis secured the naming rights as part of its agreement to lease {{convert|140000|sqft|m2|sigfig=2}} of space in the {{convert|3800000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} tower.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/07/16/willis-tower-becomes-offi_n_235939.html "Willis Tower Becomes Official: Sears Tower Renamed"], ''[[Huffington Post]]'', 17 July 2009</ref>  It was the world's tallest building from 1974 until 1998, when it was surpassed by the [[Petronas Towers]] in [[Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia]].<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=e1vL7GVGBRAC&pg=PA125&dq=%22Willis+Group+Holdings%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=14&v=onepage&q=%22Willis%20Group%20Holdings%22&f=false ''Fodor's Chicago 2010''], p. 125, Stephanie Butler, Kelly Kealy, Alexis Kelly, [[Random House]], Inc., 2009, ISBN 1-4000-0860-3. Retrieved 17 December 2009</ref>

==Operations==

Willis has 400 offices in more than 100 countries.<ref>[http://www.willis.com/About_Willis/The_Willis_Way/ Willis: The Willis Way]</ref>

==Sponsorship==
Willis Group is sponsor of The [[Willis Resilience Expedition]], a scientific program in [[Antarctica]] to better understand our changing climate and build resilience to weather-related risk.<ref name=five>[http://www.travelbite.co.uk/holiday-ideas/2013/09/30/five-minutes-with-teenage-polar-explorer-parker-liautaud Five minutes with...teen polar explorer Parker Liautaud] Travel Bite, 30 September 2013</ref>

